33:50.254 --> 33:52.021
♪ Oh... ♪

33:52.055 --> 33:54.056
♪ It's whistling ♪

33:54.091 --> 33:57.126
♪ And the whole wide world
is whistling. ♪

33:57.161 --> 33:59.462
Oh, my God.
Who wants to rub my feet?

33:59.496 --> 34:02.265
I haven't danced that hard
since Nationals two years ago.

34:02.299 --> 34:04.100
I got the DJ's number.

34:04.134 --> 34:06.302
Oh. Tina, I told you,
he's totally gay.

34:06.336 --> 34:07.537
- Come on.
- Gay?

34:07.571 --> 34:09.472
- TINA: No!
- BLAINE: What are you, blind? Tina!

34:09.505 --> 34:10.907
Uh, I'm gonna make

34:10.940 --> 34:13.376
some coffee, you guys. The
reviews come out in 30 minutes,

34:13.409 --> 34:16.045
and I want us all to go down
to the newsstand together.

34:16.079 --> 34:18.781
Uh, I'll take mine black,
thanks.

34:18.815 --> 34:20.382
(sighs)

34:22.619 --> 34:24.320
Who are all you people?

34:24.353 --> 34:26.222
Oh, my God.

34:26.255 --> 34:27.523
You are the guy... the guy

34:27.558 --> 34:29.225
that walked out
of my show last night.

34:29.259 --> 34:30.620
What are you doing
in my apartment?

34:30.627 --> 34:31.661
In my robe?

34:31.695 --> 34:32.862
Well, aren't you all

34:32.896 --> 34:35.031
so very, very rude.

34:35.065 --> 34:38.301
Oh, my God,
Sue had sex in your bed.

34:39.235 --> 34:40.636
(sniffles)

34:40.670 --> 34:42.938
Actually, we did it
all over your apartment.

34:42.973 --> 34:45.842
And if I were you, I'd put
something down on that couch

34:45.876 --> 34:46.809
before I sat on it.

34:46.844 --> 34:47.677
Oh, no, no.

34:47.710 --> 34:48.811
No, no, no, no.

34:48.846 --> 34:50.112
So, how'd the rest

34:50.147 --> 34:51.514
of the show go, huh?

34:51.547 --> 34:53.081
I considered coming back
for act two

34:53.116 --> 34:54.583
just so I could walk out again.

34:54.618 --> 34:56.686
Okay, you know what? I am not...

34:56.719 --> 35:00.341
It's okay. I got this.

35:00.376 --> 35:04.345
You made my life in high school
a living hell.

35:04.380 --> 35:05.513
Well, thank you.

35:05.548 --> 35:06.748
And it's like you had a mission

35:06.749 --> 35:08.450
to keep us underwater,

35:08.484 --> 35:10.785
never coming up,
even for a breath

35:10.820 --> 35:13.621
of air, and you said
that it was to push us,

35:13.656 --> 35:15.857
but I really don't think
that's what you wanted,

35:15.891 --> 35:18.026
because if we actually felt

35:18.060 --> 35:21.729
how wonderful and amazing
and loved we really were,

35:21.764 --> 35:23.965
then we would know
what you knew all along,

35:23.999 --> 35:27.335
which is that you are
a rotten and awful person

35:27.369 --> 35:29.704
who only finds joy
in people's misery.

35:29.738 --> 35:31.072
Well, let me
tell you something.

35:31.107 --> 35:32.474
Something amazing
happened tonight.

35:32.508 --> 35:34.109
A group of friends
rallied together

35:34.143 --> 35:35.577
and made a dream come true.

35:35.611 --> 35:39.047
And never, ever in your empty,
sad life will you feel

35:39.081 --> 35:41.182
the kind of love
that I felt tonight.

35:41.217 --> 35:42.283
And I would feel

35:42.318 --> 35:44.252
so sad for you, but I don't,

35:44.286 --> 35:46.921
because I just want you to get
the hell out of my apartment,

35:46.956 --> 35:48.876
because I want to be
with my friends.

35:51.527 --> 35:53.228
Wow.

35:53.262 --> 35:55.630
Oh, Mario, I'm sorry
you had to see that.

35:55.664 --> 35:57.398
Let's go.

35:59.034 --> 36:02.537
I suddenly don't feel
very welcome here anymore.

36:05.975 --> 36:07.942
(sighs)

36:07.977 --> 36:10.879
Well, it was, uh, super
meeting all of you.

36:11.847 --> 36:13.281
Hey, where'd you get this robe?

36:13.315 --> 36:16.518
- Just keep it.
- Thanks, bro.

36:19.853 --> 36:22.333
MERCEDES:
Ah, Rachel.

36:22.358 --> 36:23.658
Bravo.

36:23.692 --> 36:26.361
BLAINE:
Rachel. Rachel!

36:26.395 --> 36:27.996
- Rachel! Rachel!
- Yeah.

36:28.030 --> 36:30.098
Poetry... couldn't

36:30.132 --> 36:33.733
have said it better myself.
(applause, whooping)

36:35.622 --> 36:38.223
(sirens blaring)

36:38.258 --> 36:40.326
Sir, do you have
the <i> New York Times?</i>

36:40.360 --> 36:42.728
- It's the paper of record.
- How old are you?

36:42.762 --> 36:45.764
They're gonna e-mail you the <i> New</i>
<i>York Times</i> in three minutes.

36:45.799 --> 36:48.067
- What the heck?
- Just give us the paper.

36:48.101 --> 36:50.235
Oh, my God.

36:50.270 --> 36:52.304
SANTANA:
Open it.

36:52.339 --> 36:53.739
Come on.

36:53.773 --> 36:55.074
Open it!

36:55.108 --> 36:56.375
Open... I'm cold!

36:56.409 --> 36:57.543
Can you open it?

36:57.577 --> 36:58.911
Rachel, let's go,
let's read it.

36:58.945 --> 37:00.585
No, I can't, I can't.
I can't do it, Kurt.

37:00.613 --> 37:01.981
- You're gonna have to read it.
- No way!

37:02.015 --> 37:03.515
- I'm too nervous. - You know what?
Give me this.

37:03.550 --> 37:05.584
I don't mind being
the bearer of bad news.

37:05.618 --> 37:08.120
- All right.
- SANTANA: Okay.

37:08.154 --> 37:09.521
"One might ask themselves, why?

37:09.556 --> 37:10.789
"Why revive <i> Funny Girl?</i>

37:10.824 --> 37:12.925
"An iconic show
with an iconic star.

37:12.959 --> 37:15.127
"Why, when there are so many
wonderful new playwrights,

37:15.161 --> 37:17.529
"would Sidney Greene decide
to dust off this tired

37:17.564 --> 37:20.032
"old girl of a play?

37:20.066 --> 37:23.035
"Well, frankly,
I can only come up with

37:23.069 --> 37:25.070
a single answer,
and it's Rachel Berry."

37:25.105 --> 37:26.438
BLAINE:
Oh, my God.

37:26.473 --> 37:29.441
KURT: "It takes chutzpa to
be willing to step into

37:29.476 --> 37:30.843
"the Great One's
knee-high lace-ups

37:30.877 --> 37:32.044
"and make Fanny your own.

37:32.078 --> 37:34.179
"And Rachel has plenty
of that, clearly.

37:34.214 --> 37:35.974
"But she also has
something else in spades...

37:35.982 --> 37:37.182
- talent."
- Oh, my God.

37:37.217 --> 37:39.051
- SAM: Talent!
- Talent. "And mountains of it.

37:39.085 --> 37:40.552
"I'm not talking
about the Appalachians.

37:40.587 --> 37:41.787
Berry is the Alps."

37:41.821 --> 37:43.055
- Ooh.
- TINA: "I'm sure

37:43.089 --> 37:44.223
"I could find fault

37:44.257 --> 37:45.557
"in this green
actress's performance,

37:45.592 --> 37:47.472
"but shame on anyone who
would have the audacity

37:47.494 --> 37:48.994
"to criticize the bold mistakes

37:49.029 --> 37:50.763
of a supernova exploding
before our eyes."

37:50.797 --> 37:54.967
MERCEDES: "I just pray to God that no
one saw me secretly wiping my tears

37:55.001 --> 37:57.102
- No!
- "during her show-stopping 'Who Are You Now?'

37:57.137 --> 37:59.738
"I don't know where inside
that small frame Berry went

37:59.773 --> 38:02.041
"to find the emotion
she delivered with that song,

38:02.075 --> 38:04.076
but she melted the icy heart
of this reviewer."

38:04.110 --> 38:05.644
Oh, my God.
Let me see.

38:05.679 --> 38:06.912
- Okay.
- All right.

38:06.946 --> 38:08.781
"I hope this show runs
for a long time, not because

38:08.815 --> 38:10.416
"anyone needs to see
'Don't Rain on My Parade' again,

38:10.450 --> 38:11.610
"or the producers found a way

38:11.618 --> 38:12.918
"to get a real tugboat
onstage, but because

38:12.952 --> 38:14.086
"I want to have some time

38:14.120 --> 38:15.654
"to enjoy Rachel
Berry as she is now.

38:15.689 --> 38:16.922
"I know I will be going back

38:16.957 --> 38:18.590
for a second heaping bowl
of Rachel Berry."

38:18.625 --> 38:21.193
(cheering, overlapping chatter)

38:21.227 --> 38:22.361
(whooping) Yes! (phone ringing)

38:22.395 --> 38:23.696
My phone is ringing.

38:23.730 --> 38:24.863
Who's call...?

38:24.898 --> 38:26.332
Oh, it's Mr. Shue!
Oh, hey.

38:26.366 --> 38:28.667
Oh, wait. Mr. Shue,
I'm putting you on speaker!

38:28.702 --> 38:32.338
I made it back just in time
for the last few pushes.

38:32.372 --> 38:35.474
Emma's doing fine,
and so is the baby.

38:35.508 --> 38:36.642
- Okay, okay, okay.
- Yay!

38:36.676 --> 38:38.410
Shut up and just tell us
what we need to know.

38:38.445 --> 38:39.578
Boy or girl?

38:39.613 --> 38:40.746
It's a boy.

38:40.780 --> 38:42.214
(cheering
and overlapping chatter)

38:42.248 --> 38:43.716
It's a boy.

38:43.750 --> 38:45.517
Yeah, we're naming him Daniel.

38:45.552 --> 38:47.119
Daniel Finn Schuester.

38:47.153 --> 38:48.320
Aw.

38:50.590 --> 38:53.225
Hey, hey, how was...
how was the show?

38:53.259 --> 38:55.694
It was amazing.
How do you feel?

38:55.729 --> 38:57.896
(laughing)

38:57.931 --> 39:01.367
Oh, for the first time
in my life, I feel...

39:01.401 --> 39:03.369
completely happy.

39:05.071 --> 39:07.206
How about you?

39:07.240 --> 39:09.208
Same. I feel the exact same.

39:09.242 --> 39:10.809
So, I got to run.

39:10.844 --> 39:11.977
Okay, well, we love you.

39:12.012 --> 39:13.212
(overlapping chatter) ALL: Bye.

39:13.246 --> 39:14.813
Bye. Love you,
Mr. Shue.

39:14.848 --> 39:16.815
(siren blaring)

39:16.850 --> 39:19.585
So... what now?

39:19.619 --> 39:21.587
Well, it's morning.

39:21.621 --> 39:23.822
I have an early
flight to catch.

39:25.925 --> 39:29.395
Hey, I, uh... I don't
suppose I could convince you

39:29.429 --> 39:32.264
to stay in New York
a little longer.

39:32.299 --> 39:34.300
Um...

39:34.334 --> 39:37.036
No. I have a school
to run and a daughter

39:37.070 --> 39:39.505
that needs me, whose
father is Michael Bolton.

39:39.539 --> 39:41.674
Wait. What?

39:41.708 --> 39:44.610
Last night was
truly magical. I...

39:44.644 --> 39:47.212
Oh, turns out I love New York,

39:47.247 --> 39:50.082
and you are the reason why.

39:50.116 --> 39:53.052
But, Mario,
I'm a Lima gal at heart.

39:53.086 --> 39:55.688
I, uh... I love
living in a place

39:55.722 --> 39:58.891
where "Hang On, Sloopy"
is the official state song.

39:58.925 --> 40:01.994
Where the Y Bridge in Zanesville
spans the confluence

40:02.028 --> 40:04.630
of the Muskingum and
Licking Rivers, making it

40:04.664 --> 40:06.699
the only bridge in the world
that you can cross

40:06.733 --> 40:08.901
and still be
on the same side of the river.

40:08.935 --> 40:10.536
I love living in a place

40:10.570 --> 40:12.871
that is home
to the world's largest basket,

40:12.906 --> 40:16.208
located in Basket Village, USA.

40:16.243 --> 40:18.877
I guess what I'm saying, Mario,

40:18.912 --> 40:22.348
is, um, Sue Sylvester's
a big fish

40:22.382 --> 40:26.252
who really kind of likes
swimming in a little pond.

40:26.286 --> 40:28.487
I don't suppose

40:28.521 --> 40:31.690
I could convince <i> you</i>
to, uh, pull up stakes and...

40:31.725 --> 40:33.092
(sighs)

40:33.126 --> 40:36.895
Uh, you know, I'm
a New Yorker, Sue.

40:38.765 --> 40:42.234
So, uh, I guess that's it, huh?

40:42.269 --> 40:44.603
I guess so.

40:44.638 --> 40:48.908
It sure was nice getting
to know you, Sue Sylvester.

41:00.086 --> 41:02.087
(sighs)

41:04.424 --> 41:05.591
(whistles)

41:05.625 --> 41:07.326
(sighs) Yeah.

41:07.360 --> 41:09.562
So long, Sue.

41:10.597 --> 41:13.198
(sighing):
Ah.

41:13.233 --> 41:14.433
Where to, lady?

41:14.467 --> 41:17.069
Huh? I take.

41:17.103 --> 41:19.004
Ah, ah, ah.
I...

41:19.039 --> 41:21.040
Cra... crazy!

41:22.812 --> 41:24.052
Drive the car.

41:24.077 --> 41:25.210
Crazy lady.

41:25.245 --> 41:27.246
I got it. I got it.

41:29.115 --> 41:31.116
(sighs)

41:33.853 --> 41:36.255
(sighs)

41:36.289 --> 41:38.991
Thanks for making
me feel like a girl.

41:40.594 --> 41:42.161
She wasn't right...

41:42.195 --> 41:44.296
the short girl from the play.

41:44.331 --> 41:46.298
You are lovable, Sue.

41:51.338 --> 41:53.339
Let's get out of here.

41:59.512 --> 42:02.147
Recently, I've gotten
in a lot of hot water

42:02.182 --> 42:05.251
for some comments
I made on this broadcast.

42:05.285 --> 42:07.853
Last week, I called
New York City an overpriced,

42:07.888 --> 42:10.556
rat-infested hellhole that
smells like an adult diaper.

42:10.590 --> 42:12.691
Well, let me be clear.

42:12.726 --> 42:14.994
I stand by my comments.

42:15.028 --> 42:18.697
Every word I said...
absolutely true.

42:18.732 --> 42:21.133
Except for one thing.

42:21.167 --> 42:23.669
I don't hate New York.

42:23.703 --> 42:26.872
I love... New York.

42:26.907 --> 42:30.442
There's nowhere on
earth quite like it.

42:30.477 --> 42:34.613
There's no place so alive with
endless worlds of possibility.

42:34.648 --> 42:36.081
Every time you step outside,

42:36.116 --> 42:37.816
you find yourself
on an adventure

42:37.851 --> 42:39.184
you never could have predicted.

42:39.219 --> 42:41.987
Sure, you might get hit by a bus
or stop for pierogies

42:42.022 --> 42:44.623
and end up being human
trafficked by the Russian Mob,

42:44.658 --> 42:49.128
but if you're anything like this
champion cheerleading coach,

42:49.162 --> 42:52.865
you just might also find love.

42:54.134 --> 42:56.235
Or, at the very least,

42:56.269 --> 42:59.038
a night of sturdy,
spirited lovemaking

42:59.072 --> 43:01.640
with a relative stranger
in every corner of the apartment

43:01.675 --> 43:03.209
of several
of your former students.

43:03.243 --> 43:04.610
(clicks her tongue)

43:04.644 --> 43:09.027
And that's how
Sue... sees it.

